SIMPLE: rectitude
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rectitude
<hw>Rec"ti*tude</hw> <pr>(r?k"t?*t?d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>rectitudo</ets>, fr. <ets>rectus</ets> right, straight: cf. F.
<ets>rectitude</ets>. See <er>Right</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Straightness.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rightness of principle or practice; exact conformity
to truth, or to the rules prescribed for moral conduct, either by divine
or human laws; uprightness of mind; uprightness; integrity; honesty;
justice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Right judgment.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir
G. C. Lewis.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Justice</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recto-</ent>⟦br⟧
